      'The food stalls of Jemaa el-Fnaa are not a single restaurant but an unforgettable collective dining experience that has been drawing crowds for centuries. Every evening as dusk settles over the great square, hundreds of stalls spring to life with billowing clouds of charcoal smoke, sizzling grills, and the calls of hawkers beckoning diners to their tables. This is Morocco\'s most legendary eating experience and a UNESCO-recognized cultural tradition.\n\nThe stalls are arranged in rough rows, each one specializing in particular dishes. Some serve nothing but harira soup and fresh bread, others focus on grilled meats and merguez sausages, while others specialize in snail soup, sheep heads, or the famous fried fish. The most popular stalls have been in the same families for generations, their recipes refined over decades of nightly service.\n\nEating here is a full sensory immersion: the crackle of meat on charcoal, the aromatic haze of cumin and paprika, the warm glow of gas lanterns, and the surrounding carnival of musicians, storytellers, and performers. Choose a stall, sit on the communal benches, and let the cooks guide you through their specialties. The bill for a feast will rarely exceed 50 MAD per person.',
